## Skills

The procedures that satisfy the rules above live in `/skills`. `open-session` runs at the start of every session — or any time there's doubt about where the project stands — and recommends one concrete next action instead of leaving that judgment call to {{OWNER_NAME}} every time. The default sequence for any non-trivial task from there is:

`scope → design → build → verify → commit`

`verify` branches into `verify-tests` (always), `verify-evals` (only if the task involves a model call with non-deterministic output), `verify-ui` (only if the task touches a UI flow), and `verify-rls` (only if the task creates or changes a table or an access-control policy). `session-log` runs at the end of every session regardless of what else happened — the closing half of the pair `open-session` opens. `design`'s UI branch invokes `design-system`, `ux-copy`, and — when there's an existing screen to react to, or real uncertainty about user need — `design-critique` and `user-research`. These are standalone kit skills (not dependent on any Cowork plugin), so they behave identically in Claude Code and Cowork. See each skill's own file for triggers and procedure.

**Editing a skill file itself, in this repo:** in Claude Code, edit `.claude/skills/**` directly like any other file — no restriction. In a cloud Cowork session (working through the device bridge to a connected local folder), writing to `.claude/` is blocked outright by platform policy — both direct edits and the file-delivery/commit mechanism refuse it, and there's no in-session workaround (including `skill-creator`, which has no special privilege here). If a skill needs editing from a cloud Cowork session, either switch to Claude Code for that edit, or have Claude hand back the updated file as a plain attachment to copy into place manually. Cowork running natively on the project owner's own computer (no device bridge) may not hit this restriction — worth confirming per-session rather than assumed. Deletion of a skill folder isn't possible from a cloud Cowork session either way — retire a skill by overwriting its `SKILL.md` with a short stub pointing at its replacement, and leave removing the now-unused directory to a native terminal.

**If this project is worked on via Cowork alongside other projects, keep skill files genuinely generic.** Cowork's shared skill list is not scoped per project — invoking a skill by name resolves to whichever project's copy was most recently synced into that shared slot, regardless of which project is actually being worked on in that moment (confirmed directly: invoking a shared-named skill loaded one project's content while a different project's folder was the one connected). A skill that reads its specifics from this file (`CLAUDE.md` → Git conventions, Stack) rather than hardcoding them — the way `commit`, `session-log`, and the rest of the kit's skills are written — behaves correctly no matter whose copy happens to be the one that resolved. A skill that hardcodes this project's name, paths, or conventions directly into its text does not, and can silently misfire against a different project. Anything genuinely project-specific enough that it can't be written generically (a bespoke end-to-end workflow skill, for instance) should get a project-prefixed name instead of a name that could collide with another project's or the kit's own — that removes the ambiguity rather than relying on remembering which project is active.

**Kit version tracking (new in v0.9):** `.ae-kit-version` at the repo root names the kit version this project's `.claude/skills/` and `templates/` came from. See rule 12 above — check it before leaning on any generic skill's exact behavior if there's reason to think the kit has moved on since this project last synced.

## Task tracking

Not-yet-started ideas live in `BACKLOG.md` as one-line entries — no size cap, since that's exactly the file meant to absorb everything not currently being worked. When work on one actually starts, `scope` promotes it into `TASKS.md` as a full entry (id, category, status, dates, an audit log that accumulates what/when/how as work happens), where it moves through `in progress → in review`. `TASKS.md` holds only that live work by design, so it stays short.

The moment a task reaches `done`, `commit` moves it out of `TASKS.md` into `TASKS_ARCHIVE.md` immediately — not at session end. `TASKS_ARCHIVE.md` splits once it reaches 50 entries: the older batch moves into `tasks-archive/TASKS_ARCHIVE_{start}_{end}.md` (a dedicated subfolder, created the first time this happens, so the project root doesn't accumulate a growing pile of dated archive files over the project's life), tracked in `TASKS_ARCHIVE_INDEX.md`. Check the current `TASKS_ARCHIVE.md` first when looking for something completed recently; the index only matters for something further back.

Session logs follow the same shape: `/logs/` holds the most recent 30 sessions, one file per session; older ones move to `/logs/archive/` (no separate index needed there — the date's already in each file name). `STATUS.md` always reflects current state at a glance, referencing only the most recent log.

None of this is optional busywork — it's {{OWNER_NAME}}'s primary review surface, kept fast to scan by construction rather than by discipline alone.
